<section class="w-full px-4 md:px-8 mb-12">
  <div class="border-b border-black pb-8">
    <div class="flex items-center justify-center mb-8">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-3xl md:text-5xl font-bold uppercase border-y border-black py-2 px-8 inline-block">
        Our Story
      </h2>
    </div>
    
    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-8 columns-1 md:columns-2 gap-x-8">
      <div class="font-serif text-lg leading-relaxed text-justify mb-4">
        <p class="mb-4">
          In a development unlikely to trouble national headlines, Indiefluence began when a lone, caffeine-fortified creator decided the digital world needed a touch more thought and a lot less noise. What started as a modest experiment in ideas soon gathered a quiet momentum of its own. One desk became a workspace, a workspace became a calling, and before long, an accidental venture had turned into a team determined to make meaning out of the internet’s disorder.
        </p>
        <p class="mb-4">
          As history books will almost certainly forget to mention, new voices soon joined the Indiefluence table—each bringing opinions strong enough to unsettle furniture and ideas bright enough to justify the noise. What began as cautious collaboration turned into a pleasant sort of creative disorder.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="font-serif text-lg leading-relaxed text-justify mb-4">
        <p class="mb-4">
          Projects grew bolder, debates grew longer, and the team discovered that progress rarely looks glamorous. More often, it resembles several people arguing politely over coffee until the right thought finally appears.
        </p>
        <p class="mb-4">
          In time, this lively assembly evolved into something resembling an organisation, though no one remembers exactly when that happened. What they do recall is the shared belief that brands deserved substance, not shortcuts. With every campaign, the group sharpened its craft, learned its quirks, and somehow avoided setting anything on fire. Indiefluence became less a workplace and more a newsroom of restless minds—quietly convinced that thoughtful work can, on good days, make a louder difference.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
